WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.960
Thank you. So, I'm going to go ahead and give my number one takeaway before I even

00:00:07.960 --> 00:00:12.440
get started, and that is, if you choose to speak at a conference next year and have to

00:00:12.440 --> 00:00:18.200
be on stage, do not forget a belt, because I'm having a really tough time at the moment.

00:00:18.200 --> 00:00:23.120
Anyways, let's get started. So, I'm Blake. I'm Director of Analytics and Data Science

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:26.760
at Suffolk Construction in Boston, and today we're going to talk a little bit about app

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:32.680
development and polyglot environments. So, I want to start with a story or situation

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:38.320
that might be familiar to you. Say you're at work in a meeting or at lunch or in between

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:42.639
meetings and you hear some people chatting about a challenge that they're facing that

00:00:42.639 --> 00:00:47.439
can't quite be solved with the data tools that are currently in place. Maybe it requires

00:00:47.439 --> 00:00:52.419
some on-the-fly data manipulation that Tableau can't quite handle, or the data's too unwieldy

00:00:52.419 --> 00:00:56.980
to handle in Excel, whatever it is, but you think, you know, I can build an app to solve

00:00:56.980 --> 00:01:04.860
that. So, you do, and it does. So, your app's a home run. You know, the business loves it.

00:01:04.860 --> 00:01:09.940
Adoption grows. It's really spreading by word of mouth, you know, real grassroots success

00:01:09.940 --> 00:01:16.900
story. Way more popular than you could possibly imagine when you started. So, you knock out

00:01:16.900 --> 00:01:22.180
a few easy wins, you know, tackle some low-hanging fruit, thinking that will kind of calm the

00:01:22.180 --> 00:01:27.620
noise, but instead, demand continues to snowball, right? New feature requests, requests for

00:01:27.620 --> 00:01:33.300
other integrations, kind of a nonstop stream of UI tweaks or enhancements. It's all coming

00:01:33.300 --> 00:01:39.540
faster than you can handle. And now, your once kind of simple, beautiful app has turned

00:01:39.540 --> 00:01:45.739
into a hot mess, right? You have kind of esoteric code paths that only you can follow, a litany

00:01:45.739 --> 00:01:50.900
of like half-baked, half-implemented features, and still way too many demands for you to

00:01:51.099 --> 00:01:56.900
handle. So, now, you know, you're burnt out, your users are frustrated, and kind of progress

00:01:56.900 --> 00:02:04.459
has grinded to a halt. And the worst part is, you know, it didn't really feel catastrophic

00:02:04.459 --> 00:02:08.460
along the way. It was probably quite the opposite, maybe even like a little euphoric. You know,

00:02:08.460 --> 00:02:12.500
you had really engaged users. The feedback you were getting was positive. They were just

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:17.339
kind of little tweaks along the way until suddenly, you're at a boiling point, right?

00:02:17.779 --> 00:02:22.139
What started as a win has now become kind of unsustainable. So, that's what we want

00:02:22.139 --> 00:02:26.419
to focus on today, kind of a real-world example of that that we ran into at Suffolk and how

00:02:26.419 --> 00:02:33.100
we try to catch and combat those scenarios. So, I think when most people, or at least

00:02:33.100 --> 00:02:37.179
historically, maybe not in this session, talk about polyglot environments, they think most

00:02:37.179 --> 00:02:41.699
about developer choice and flexibility, but that's really only half of the equation.

00:02:41.699 --> 00:02:45.619
I think what often gets overlooked is how tools like Workbench and especially Connect

00:02:46.059 --> 00:02:52.139
can really be leveraged to help you deploy apps at scale. And the sweet spot would be

00:02:52.139 --> 00:02:58.460
marrying smart app design with the right polyglot strategy to move from, you know, a MVP to

00:02:58.460 --> 00:03:02.699
a fully-featured deployed product. So, that's what we'll unpack a little bit today in the

00:03:02.699 --> 00:03:08.979
approach that we take at Suffolk. So, let's talk about the real-world example that I mentioned.

00:03:08.979 --> 00:03:15.380
This is Primavera P6. It's kind of the go-to de facto standard for scheduling data in the

00:03:15.380 --> 00:03:21.660
construction industry. Primavera was acquired by Oracle in the early 2000s, and honestly,

00:03:21.660 --> 00:03:26.539
I don't know if they've touched it since then. So, there's a few, you know, it presents

00:03:26.539 --> 00:03:32.500
a few challenges. One is it's rather expensive, so we have limited licenses. Two, at least

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:36.460
in the Suffolk instance, it does not run in the browser, so, you know, all the joys of

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:42.460
enterprise software management, it also only runs on Windows. And three, even if you were

00:03:42.460 --> 00:03:46.460
able to get a license and have it installed, it is really not the most user-friendly or

00:03:46.460 --> 00:03:53.740
intuitive tool. So, all this, you know, combines together to create a problem for people in

00:03:53.740 --> 00:03:58.619
our company to interact with scheduled data in any kind of meaningful way. It's mostly

00:03:58.619 --> 00:04:04.740
disseminated through, you know, PDF screenshots or Excel dumps. So, this is a situation, you

00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:07.860
know, I thought we definitely have the data, so we could probably build something to help

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:14.139
out here. So, that's what we did. We built a very rudimentary Gantt chart. Then we had

00:04:14.139 --> 00:04:18.220
to add some filtering to it. Then the first big pivot where people were saying, well,

00:04:18.220 --> 00:04:22.579
instead of just reading schedules, can we create schedules, which necessitated, you

00:04:22.579 --> 00:04:28.220
know, a bunch of drop-downs and sliders for inputs to get data about the schedules, and

00:04:28.220 --> 00:04:33.019
then once we were generating schedules, we needed summary tabs for it, and then this

00:04:33.019 --> 00:04:37.179
all became overwhelming, so people said, can we just chat with the interface instead of

00:04:37.179 --> 00:04:42.739
having to use all these widgets we asked for? And all the while, we're still, you know,

00:04:42.739 --> 00:04:48.339
iterating over the visual style of our app. And when it started kind of as a very simplistic

00:04:48.339 --> 00:04:55.059
shiny app, suddenly became something much, much more than that. Right? And this kind

00:04:55.059 --> 00:04:58.940
of, like, is on top of what we talked about. So, like, this is, we're obviously not using

00:04:58.940 --> 00:05:03.619
any kind of modular or components in this. It's just, like, one more thing we kept adding.

00:05:03.619 --> 00:05:08.019
So it's important to remember here as well that, you know, our team is not a team of

00:05:08.019 --> 00:05:11.859
software engineers. We're data analysts and data scientists, and while we try to adhere

00:05:11.859 --> 00:05:17.140
to best practices, you know, most of the team's experience with things like GitHub are as

00:05:17.140 --> 00:05:21.820
solo practitioners, so when you have people trying to work together, you know, invariably

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:26.019
we end up with problems like this, which, you know, even seeing them now raises the

00:05:26.019 --> 00:05:31.100
hair on the back of my neck. So I'd like to think our team has a very, you know, measured

00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:36.179
approach to resolving this, but in practice, you know, people's first gut reaction is something

00:05:36.179 --> 00:05:41.220
more like this. So that's kind of the conundrum we're stuck with, right? Like, how do we enable

00:05:41.220 --> 00:05:48.220
app development to scale with business demand? And the way that we try to approach it is,

00:05:48.220 --> 00:05:51.859
you know, reframe the problem. So it's no longer this one-off app that we built that

00:05:51.859 --> 00:05:56.140
we're chasing our tail around, trying to keep up with demand, but take a step back and think

00:05:56.140 --> 00:06:01.899
of it as a product we want to grow and sustain and stick around for the business for a while.

00:06:01.899 --> 00:06:07.920
So that reframing requires three things, right? So smart app design, a plan for moving deliberately

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:15.420
from a proof of concept to an MVP to our fully featured product. Technical separation, leveraging

00:06:15.420 --> 00:06:21.700
APIs and internal packages that make our work independent and language agnostic. And team

00:06:21.700 --> 00:06:27.899
scalability. So how do we create space for multiple developers or teams to work in parallel?

00:06:27.899 --> 00:06:34.260
All right. So that kind of reframing allows us to go from that monstrosity of a monolithic

00:06:34.260 --> 00:06:39.700
single file app that you see, that we saw before, to something that would scale in both

00:06:39.700 --> 00:06:44.619
functionality and complexity, all with, like, individual discrete domains that can kind

00:06:44.619 --> 00:06:48.980
of be worked independently.

00:06:48.980 --> 00:06:55.140
So let's talk about how these pillars help us accomplish that. First, we'll talk about

00:06:55.140 --> 00:07:00.579
app design. So some of you might be familiar with this sketch from Henrik Nyberg about

00:07:00.579 --> 00:07:07.140
the principles of MVPs, minimum viable product, and the idea being that we want to move away

00:07:07.140 --> 00:07:13.619
from kind of Big Bang delivery, you know, iterative development that does not deliver

00:07:13.619 --> 00:07:18.899
anything to the client until the very end, to a much more iterative and incremental approach,

00:07:18.899 --> 00:07:24.500
really tightly coupled around the core functionality of the needs of the user. That leaves us room

00:07:24.500 --> 00:07:27.660
to scale.

00:07:27.660 --> 00:07:31.540
And as well-intentioned as we are with this approach, sometimes, you know, you build a

00:07:31.540 --> 00:07:36.700
proof of concept and you end up with something like this, which is maybe somewhere in between,

00:07:36.700 --> 00:07:40.619
right? We have a happy customer, but we've built, like, a tool that has really maybe

00:07:40.619 --> 00:07:47.820
limited us in how we can scale. And I often fall victim to this, and I think it's okay

00:07:47.820 --> 00:07:53.019
for us to say that, you know, while it's great if our proof of concept scales into

00:07:53.019 --> 00:07:58.420
our MVP, it's not a necessity. They serve two different purposes, right?

00:07:58.420 --> 00:08:05.540
So our proof of concept is about proving viability and getting kind of buy-in from our customers.

00:08:05.540 --> 00:08:09.500
So a lot of times, that's scrappy, you're cutting corners, you just want to get something

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:14.700
out there. It's not necessarily adhering to best practices. And MVP is about building

00:08:14.700 --> 00:08:18.980
a foundation that will scale and support, you know, more complex functionality in the

00:08:18.980 --> 00:08:24.760
future. So again, while it's great if it does scale, I think, you know, open communications

00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:27.779
with your business stakeholders to say that we're going to reset after we've gotten

00:08:27.779 --> 00:08:31.660
buy-in is a critical part.

00:08:31.660 --> 00:08:36.260
So if design is about planning for scale, the next question is, how do we make that

00:08:36.260 --> 00:08:43.260
scaling possible? And that's where APIs and packages come into play. So, you know,

00:08:43.260 --> 00:08:47.820
I'm sure you're all familiar with, there's a bunch of different variants of it, but first

00:08:47.820 --> 00:08:51.659
time you write code, you write it. Second time, you copy it. Third time, turn it into

00:08:51.659 --> 00:08:59.179
a function. So APIs and packages are where we implement that, right? So it's our place

00:08:59.179 --> 00:09:04.419
to write code once and make it trustworthy and usable throughout all our environments.

00:09:04.419 --> 00:09:09.700
And internal packages are kind of the helper function or where we kind of house our helper

00:09:09.700 --> 00:09:16.140
functions that developers use day in and day out, again and again. So our approach at Suffolk

00:09:16.140 --> 00:09:23.299
is to maintain packages in both R and Python that have feature parity across both of them.

00:09:23.299 --> 00:09:26.619
And that ensures that, you know, developers in each of their languages have the tools

00:09:26.619 --> 00:09:31.260
available to them that they need.

00:09:31.260 --> 00:09:34.900
So kind of a real world example of this, you know, we use Databricks as a data warehouse.

00:09:34.900 --> 00:09:42.659
If you've ever seen, like, the Posit Connect cookbook on implementation across, you know,

00:09:42.659 --> 00:09:50.460
the Python version versus the R version, the mechanisms are similar, but the implementation

00:09:50.460 --> 00:09:57.020
is quite different. So, you know, if I was a Python developer and I went to go to R,

00:09:57.020 --> 00:10:01.099
at best I might be a little confused. At worst, I might just shut it down and go back

00:10:01.099 --> 00:10:07.099
to Python. So our thought was, you know, was alluded to, like, while there is a lot of

00:10:07.099 --> 00:10:11.940
similarities, can we make them even more similar? So we wrappered those both in functions internally

00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:18.179
so they're exactly the same across both. And that proved to be really successful. So

00:10:18.179 --> 00:10:23.739
we took that, looked across, like, the ecosystem for kind of other similar examples and started

00:10:23.739 --> 00:10:30.059
wrappering some other packages as well. So, you know, responses from Vetiver, reading,

00:10:30.059 --> 00:10:37.979
writing, setting permissions on pins, and most recently, ChatList and Elmer, the interface.

00:10:37.979 --> 00:10:42.419
The other additional benefit of this is because these are internal packages, we can make very

00:10:42.419 --> 00:10:49.140
opinionated decisions about the functions we expose and the values that we set in them.

00:10:49.140 --> 00:10:53.900
So, you know, model choices, where we write pins, those kind of things, we can remove

00:10:53.900 --> 00:10:58.940
away and make sure we have a standard implementation. But the other ancillary benefit we've seen

00:10:58.940 --> 00:11:06.940
to this is that, you know, this dual package strategy has really kind of enabled our aspiring

00:11:06.940 --> 00:11:11.859
polyglot developers to be more comfortable trying their less familiar language because

00:11:11.859 --> 00:11:19.460
it's one less bit of cognitive load that they have to worry about.

00:11:19.460 --> 00:11:25.700
So if packages are kind of our helper functions inside of an app, APIs are our super functions

00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:32.500
that make that functionality available anywhere. So, you know, another kind of ‑‑ whoops,

00:11:32.500 --> 00:11:37.219
back to a little too quick. As a best practice, you've probably seen this before, we've implemented

00:11:37.299 --> 00:11:43.900
this call twice, so as a good developer, maybe I move it to a function, and kind of the next

00:11:43.900 --> 00:11:49.700
step we take is the thought of, like, okay, does this function meet two criteria? One,

00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:54.940
is there a value in it besides in this app itself? And do we envision a roadmap of it

00:11:54.940 --> 00:11:59.859
that makes it ‑‑ that there's additional complexity that, you know, has the chance

00:11:59.859 --> 00:12:06.940
to grow, probably would benefit from individual developer focus.

00:12:06.940 --> 00:12:10.020
And the idea is that, you know, it's the same input, same outputs, but it's callable

00:12:10.020 --> 00:12:16.580
from any environment, whether it's R or Python or even somewhere beyond. The other benefit

00:12:16.580 --> 00:12:20.539
of it is that at that point, then, you no longer need to be as concerned about the underlying

00:12:20.539 --> 00:12:24.900
mechanisms once it's removed from the app. You just kind of need to know the schema and

00:12:24.900 --> 00:12:29.200
the end point and hopefully functionality continues to work.

00:12:29.200 --> 00:12:33.419
So this is a real example that we did again where we had, you know, a call built into

00:12:33.419 --> 00:12:40.020
the app. We extracted it to an API end point deployed on Connect. It was originally an

00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:47.659
R model deployed with Vetiver and Plumber. It eventually migrated to a Python model deployed

00:12:47.659 --> 00:12:54.219
with Vetiver and FastAPI, and then eventually the complexity of it was a FastAPI that not

00:12:54.219 --> 00:12:59.219
only used Vetiver but other business logic embedded in it. But the key feature is that

00:12:59.219 --> 00:13:02.500
the apps themselves that were using it would never have to change, right? Like the end

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:14.179
point stayed the same. So we can have smart design and technical separation, but without

00:13:14.179 --> 00:13:19.219
a way to work in parallel, we'd still be bottlenecked.

00:13:19.219 --> 00:13:26.380
So how we unblock teams isn't really magic. It's agreement, and, you know, we think of

00:13:26.380 --> 00:13:30.380
agreement in terms of kind of like a contract, not a literal actual contract. People aren't

00:13:30.380 --> 00:13:35.859
signing papers, but kind of like more akin to like a data contract. So, you know, an

00:13:35.859 --> 00:13:40.700
agreement of the inputs and outputs of a particular function, and that way if I'm, you know,

00:13:40.700 --> 00:13:47.179
developing services and you're developing the UI, we both know what to expect.

00:13:47.179 --> 00:13:52.619
So for us, APIs are where those boundaries are defined. They're the agreement that says,

00:13:52.619 --> 00:13:58.460
you know, you hand me this, I will return that to you, and it doesn't matter if the

00:13:58.460 --> 00:14:04.820
API is like half-baked, hard-coded at the start with, or in various stages of development.

00:14:04.820 --> 00:14:08.340
The important part is we have an agreement so everyone can continue to move forward on

00:14:08.340 --> 00:14:12.679
their own. And in that sense, every kind of API becomes

00:14:12.679 --> 00:14:17.979
its own mini-MVP, which, you know, again, as long as we can agree on the schema, the

00:14:17.979 --> 00:14:24.099
payload, and the endpoints, it can continue to iterate over time, and those other downstream

00:14:24.099 --> 00:14:31.780
teams can wire up to it knowing that it will evolve without breaking.

00:14:31.780 --> 00:14:35.820
So once we have those contracts in place, that's kind of where scalability can kick

00:14:35.820 --> 00:14:42.619
in, and we no longer have a single developer as a bottleneck. So we can have back-end teams

00:14:42.619 --> 00:14:48.219
developing APIs, we can have package teams continuing to polish our internal functions,

00:14:48.219 --> 00:14:54.340
UI teams continuing to add functionality and features to our Shiny apps, and they can all

00:14:54.340 --> 00:14:59.659
move forward together as a whole. And the important thing is also those contracts

00:14:59.659 --> 00:15:06.099
don't enforce any particular language, right? Like the agreement is the boundary, not the

00:15:06.099 --> 00:15:11.940
implementation. So if I'm comfortable working in R, I can develop in R, there's a package

00:15:11.940 --> 00:15:18.299
in Python, I can freely use Python, the right tool can be used for the right job without

00:15:18.299 --> 00:15:24.179
creating chaos. It's also not just about language. It's

00:15:24.179 --> 00:15:30.419
all about, you know, process as well. So, you know, if we have a team thick in the middle

00:15:30.419 --> 00:15:36.419
of app development, maybe we'll use Sprint or Agile. If it's a more mature API, maybe

00:15:36.419 --> 00:15:41.780
they use Kanban to manage their backlog. If I have a smaller piece, maybe I use something

00:15:41.780 --> 00:15:47.500
even more lightweight. The important part is, like, we do not overstandardize. We allow

00:15:47.500 --> 00:15:53.900
teams the flexibility to deliver by what makes sense for that team.

00:15:53.900 --> 00:15:59.099
So once we have this all in place, it's not just about scaling one app with one team.

00:15:59.099 --> 00:16:04.820
We're creating an ecosystem that allows for multiple apps, multiple processes, you know,

00:16:04.820 --> 00:16:09.859
multiple stacks to kind of all work in parallel and evolve at the same time.

00:16:09.859 --> 00:16:14.020
To me, that's really what scalability is about. There's some aspect of speed to it,

00:16:14.020 --> 00:16:18.539
but it's really about creating an environment that many approaches can move forward together

00:16:18.539 --> 00:16:24.580
in harmony. So, you know, it sounds really easy. You put

00:16:24.580 --> 00:16:33.179
it on slides, but in practice, it takes a lot of discipline. And that discipline really

00:16:33.179 --> 00:16:38.219
is dependent on a few things. So to accomplish that, you know, we need clear communication

00:16:38.219 --> 00:16:44.460
around these contracts, all of which can be facilitated by constant communication and

00:16:44.460 --> 00:16:48.940
transparency across these teams and developers who are working on the different pieces.

00:16:48.940 --> 00:16:53.679
And then finally, I think this is all enabled by this idea of shifting from a code-first

00:16:53.679 --> 00:16:59.039
mindset to a product-first mindset. And the way I think of that is, you know, historically

00:16:59.039 --> 00:17:04.939
the way I've worked is I have this idea, I open up RStudio, and I just start writing

00:17:04.939 --> 00:17:09.420
with a hope that I'm going to get to what I want to get to at some point. And this is

00:17:09.420 --> 00:17:13.780
kind of shifting that, right? So even in that mindset, I'm still doing design, but it's

00:17:13.780 --> 00:17:17.260
like design at every step along the way. What we want to do is shift all of that in the

00:17:17.260 --> 00:17:22.180
aggregate to up front so we can all kind of decide on what the best plan is for implementation

00:17:22.180 --> 00:17:29.819
of this product as a whole. Okay. I will say, you know, in addition to

00:17:29.819 --> 00:17:33.699
the change in just the process, obviously there are some technical considerations to

00:17:33.699 --> 00:17:38.219
think about. You know, moving everything out of app to APIs does have some performance

00:17:38.219 --> 00:17:43.739
or response time concerns to think about. Other things like versioning feature flags,

00:17:43.739 --> 00:17:47.459
you know, those are all important details to make this work at scale that have to be

00:17:47.459 --> 00:17:52.540
considered. But, you know, we started today with a story

00:17:52.540 --> 00:17:56.339
that you've probably lived to some degree yourself. You know, a quick app that snowballs

00:17:56.339 --> 00:18:01.540
into something unsustainable. We talk about the way out of that trap being for us to design

00:18:01.540 --> 00:18:08.219
deliberately, abstract smartly, and scale responsibly. You know, that means treating

00:18:08.219 --> 00:18:16.339
our proof of concepts as experiments and our MVPs as foundations. It means moving our helper

00:18:16.339 --> 00:18:21.380
functions into these internal packages and our core functionality into these super functions

00:18:21.380 --> 00:18:27.979
as APIs. And it means giving our teams the space and structure to work in parallel without

00:18:27.979 --> 00:18:35.020
chaos. And languages like R and Python and platforms and tools like, you know, Connect

00:18:35.020 --> 00:18:40.900
and Workbench are instrumental in making and helping us scale. But it's really the discipline

00:18:40.900 --> 00:18:45.500
about these contracts, communications, and a product-first mindset that makes scaling

00:18:45.500 --> 00:18:50.219
stick. And hopefully we'll turn our, you know, initial four-act horror story into kind of

00:18:50.219 --> 00:18:59.180
a feel-good rom-com that we all want to be part of. That's it. Thank you.

00:18:59.180 --> 00:19:07.739
Okay. We have� well, there's two questions related to testing. I'll paraphrase the one.

00:19:07.739 --> 00:19:13.459
It seems like a pretty complex app. So what was your testing process like? And the second

00:19:13.459 --> 00:19:18.540
one was after migrating functionality from an R package to an API, how do you adjust

00:19:18.540 --> 00:19:23.500
